name  Grange Lodge Hotel   description  “All Jews to report to the Grange Lodge Hotel”   Note:  It is thought that Grange Lodge Hotel was built as a private house, in about 1815, using the profits made from privateering.   It stayed in the same hands until purchased by the Mansell family in the 1930s. From this time it was run as a hotel apart from a five year break during the German Occupation (1940-45). During that period the hotel was used as the headquarters for the German Feld Kommandant.  A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website www.visitguernsey.

name  Dehus Dolmen   description  “Guernsey is very beautiful in all its variety - fields, woods, hedgerows, dells, manors, dolmens, wild cliffs, witches corners, Tudor Houses and Norman stone cottages.”   Note  Dehus Dolmen is a European megalithic marvel. Open to the public with lights and an interpretation board. Well worth a visit as it is one of the best preserved burial chambers in Europe.   A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website: www.visitguernsey.com

name  Candie Gardens   description  “We started to go along Candie Gardens, and there everything changed  - carnival to nightmare.”   Note:  Candie Gardens is a St Peter Port hidden green space and contains the Guernsey Museum (www.museums.gov.gg) and the Priaulx Library.   For those of you interested in Guernsey history this is the perfect place to spend hours looking, experiencing and reading.   A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website www.visitguernsey.com

name  Liberation Monument    description  A monument built to mark the 50th anniversary of the Liberation of Guernsey, 9th May, 1995.   It stands where the liberating British forces were greeted by the Guernsey people in 1945.  It is a sundial and consists of 50 layers of Guernsey granite and is five meters high.  On the 9th May each year, the shadow of the obelisk falls on inscriptions on the granite seating marking the events of Liberation Day 1945.  A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website: www.visitguernsey.com

name  North Esplanade   description  “North Esplanade was filled with soldiers too”   Note:  The North Esplanade is the St Peter Port front. At the Northern end near the Weighbridge there is a long forgotten fact that a large gun emplacement sat in the window of the pub called the White Hart. Diners in that establishment gazing out onto the roundabout and the Weighbridge clock tower are probably unaware that the semi circular window is actually a German gun emplacement.   A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website: www.visitguernsey.com

name  Little Chapel   description  “Dawsey took me to a tiny church - every inch of which is a mosaic of broken china and smashed pottery.”   Note:  A work of art and a labour of love, the Little Chapel is possibly the smallest chapel in the world. It was built by Brother Déodat who started work in March 1914. His plan was to create a miniature version of the famous grotto and basilica at Lourdes in France. Guardianship of the Little Chapel now rests with Blanchelande Girls College which is run by a Charitable Trust.   The Little Chapel is beautifully decorated with seashells, pebbles and colourful pieces of broken china and the College has an ongoing programme of repairs and improvements.   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Chapel  A community project by www.submarine.gg.  Please contact nemo@submarine.gg with feedback.  Official Guernsey Tourism Website: www.visitguernsey.com
